In all seriousness, my opinion is that it badly, badly, needs an editor. As much as that, it needs a rewrite. The plot as it stands is just sort of like this vine randomly growing across the ground and around a tree, and only seems to exist to create a pretext for the author to write scenes exploring a really obvious TF fetish. Man and wife on rural farm are abducted by ayylmaos, who just happen to be cute fuzzy anthro foxes instead of bug-eyed Roswell Greys or Little Green Men from Mars. But wait, while they're drugged and unconscious, a micrometeor smashes through the ship and kills the woman! But wait, the ayylmaos just happen to have made data recordings of their brains, and they just happen to have a spare cloned fox woman body in the freezer they were keeping in case anyone needed organs replaced. But wait, they can install Windows, I mean, the woman's recorded mind, on the clone. Then put them back in their house and fly away, leaving them thinking she was magically transmogrified into a fox overnight. But wait, the ayylmaos come back. But wait, the guy and his wife are suspiciously reasonable about this and agree to have adventures. But wait, the government gets involved. But wait, there's a big gun battle. And on and on.

This happens, and then that happens, and it feels less like a coherent story than a series of scenes. Worse than that, the mood becomes dark in the last few chapters, which I think were written just after 9/11. Suddenly a character is thrown in, suddenly he isn't what he seems, suddenly there are high stakes and a life-or-death mission, blood and thunder. And after that is resolved, right after that, I perceive that the author said "welp, this is a good place to stop."

I don't even know if the author is still alive. His web page doesn't seem to have been updated in almost twenty years, which raises questions. I think there are characters you may like meeting. I liked Chessec and Marie. I'd like to see a good rewrite.
